<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Christopher Report Spawns `Cautious Optimism' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Christopher Report Spawns `Cautious Optimism' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1705053894 Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew 17 May 94 
pp 1, 19 </F>

<F P=103> TA1705053894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Shim'on Schiffer] </F>
  [Excerpt] For the first time since the beginning of the 
Israeli-Syrian negotiations, high-ranking political sources last 
night voiced "cautious optimism" concerning the contacts with 
Damascus. 
  U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher, who arrived in 
Israel yesterday afternoon after a series of talks with 
President al-Asad and Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar' in 
Damascus, met with Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin at his Jerusalem 
residence late last night. The meeting, which was attended by 
Dennis Ross and Professor Itamar Rabinovich, lasted about an 
hour and a half. 
  After the meeting, Itamar Rabinovich, Israel's ambassador to 
the United States, said: "The negotiations held in Damascus 
should be viewed as a few more small steps at the start of a 
long trek. Further declarations were made and answers given in 
the course of Christopher's talks. The talks should be viewed 
in terms of protracted negotiations. Not every declaration or 
answer immediately creates a new reality." 
  Nevertheless, last night both American and Israeli sources 
were under the impression that practical Israeli-Syrian 
negotiations have been launched and that while the gaps between 
the parties' stands are very profound, Christopher sensed that 
the Syrian stand has shifted. 
  Last night, Christopher presented Rabin with detailed Syrian 
answers to the clarifications Israel had requested concerning 
the arrangement proposed by Syria. [passage omitted] 
  [Reporting on Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 0405 GMT 
on 
17 May, political correspondent Shlomo Raz states that 
"Jerusalem primarily took note of the Syrian media reports, 
which are also being interpreted as an attempt to improve the 
atmosphere and not as actual progress in the negotiations. 
These include the TISHRIN report about withdrawal within a 
reasonable period and the AL-HAYAH report outlining five points 
of the Israeli-Syrian peace arrangement." Raz cites "a senior 
political source" as saying that the AL-HAYAH report "is 
inaccurate, because that is not what Warren Christopher brought 
back from Damascus, although it indicates a desire to improve 
the atmosphere." 
  [Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew on 17 May, in a report by 
political correspondent Aluf Ben on page A1, cites "a senior 
political element" as saying "last night" that "the Syrian 
replies addressed every component of the Israeli peace proposal: 
withdrawal, security arrangements, the substance of peace, the 
time factor, and the linkage between withdrawal and 
normalization. According to him, the answers were `low key'."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-59709 </DOCNO>
