Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visit of Kazakhstani Prime Minister Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Visit of Kazakhstani Prime Minister Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Important' Trade Ties Lauded </H4>

<F P=102> LD1605160994 Tehran IRNA in English 1510 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1605160994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, May 16, IRNA -- President Akbar 
Hashemi-Rafsanjani termed as "important" Kazakhstan's links with 
Iran's Caspian Sea provinces in further activating the trade 
ties between the private sectors of the two countries. 
  The president made the remark here monday in his meeting 
with 
visiting Kazakh premier, Sergey Tereshchenko. He described as 
positive the political will existing in both the countries for 
strengthening of mutual cooperation and called for putting into 
practice the agreements reached between Tehran and Almaty. 
  The president referred to the setting up of a free trade 
zone 
at the port city of Bandar Anzali, and said this would greatly 
strengthen Kazakhstan's links with Iran's Caspian provinces of 
Gilan and Mazandaran by facilitating trade exchanges and making 
the private sectors of the two countries more involved. The 
decision to declare Bandar Anzali as free trade zone was taken 
yesterday at the end of the president's inspection tour of Gilan 
Province. 
  The southern shores of the oblong Caspian, the world's 
largest inland sea, are hemmed in by Iran, while the northern 
and part of the northeastern shores forms the Kazakhstan 
coastline. 
  The other three countries with access to Caspian waters are 
the Russian Federation on the northwest, the Azerbaijan Republic 
on the southwest and Turkmenistan on the southeast. 
  Tereshchenko who arrived in Tehran on Saturday, submitted 
Rafsanjani a message from Kazakh President Nursultan Nazarbayev 
and said Tehran-Almaty ties had further expanded especially 
after Nazarbayev's visit to Iran. 
  He said Iran's valuable experiences in establishing 
industries and re-activating factories was very useful for his 
country. 
  Raising the volume of Tehran-Almaty wheat and coal exchanges 
in the long-term, Kazakhstan's purchase of copper and 
fire-resistant material from Iran, joint production of engine 
oil and expanding road, rail, shipping and air transportation 
between the two countries were among the topics Tereshchenko 
discussed with Iranian officials. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

