<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Civilian Powers in Gaza Strip Transferred </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Civilian Powers in Gaza Strip Transferred </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1805095294 Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew 18 May 94 p 
8 </F>

<F P=103> TA1805095294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by David Regev] </F>
  [Excerpts] As of 1400 yesterday, the Palestinians in the 
Gaza Strip have been running their own lives. 
  Thirty-four civilian offices were handed over to the 
Palestinians in a lengthy ceremony held at the Civil 
Administration's new offices in the Erez industrial zone, and 
the Israeli Civil Administration in the Gaza Strip officially 
became the civilian liaison center between Israel and the 
Palestinians. 
  The civilian Palestinian Authority in the Gaza Strip is 
headed by Dr. Zakariya al-Agha, Attorney Furayh Abu-Middayn, and 
Dr. Riyad al-Za'nun. The three will operate out of a new office 
set up near the Palestinian police building in Gaza. 
Forty-eight vehicles to be used by the Palestinian Authority 
arrived in the Gaza Strip yesterday from Egypt. 
  The first decisions passed by the Palestinian Authority were 
to declare Friday the official day of rest and the days of Id 
al-Adha a holiday. [passage omitted] 
  After an initial meeting between the sides, representatives 
of the Israeli offices and their Palestinian counterparts 
proceeded to sign the transfer of powers. Representatives of 34 
offices -- transportation, education, treasury, interior, 
health, and others -- spent four long hours signing the letters 
of empowerment written in English. 
  The civilian powers were officially handed over to the 
Palestinians after Brigadier General Dov Gazit, head of the 
Civil Administration, and Palestinian representative Frayj 
al-Khayri signed the letters. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

