<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Arafat Remarks on Jihad, Jerusalem Draw Reaction </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Arafat Remarks on Jihad, Jerusalem Draw Reaction </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Sha'th on Interpretation of Remarks </H4>

<F P=102> JN1805100994 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Arabic 0930 GMT 18 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1805100994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political adviser to PLO chairman, 
today said Yasir 'Arafat and other PLO leaders will arrive in 
the self-rule area in the Gaza Strip during the first half of 
next month. 
  In a telephone interview from Cairo with our correspondent 
Sa'id Mu'addi, Dr. Sha'th said reports received from the Gaza 
Strip and Jericho show things are going very well. The same 
applies to the reports he received from Major General Amnon 
Shahaq, head of the Israeli negotiations team, he added. 
  Asked about 'Arafat's statements in Johannesburg, in which 
he 
called for jihad to liberate Jerusalem, Dr. Sha'th said there 
are things which are sometimes interpreted in an exaggerated 
manner. 
  Dr. Sha'th said the PLO decided to form the Palestinian 
authority at this stage from those who have already been chosen 
until the other members of this authority are named. He added 
that negotiations on the transfer of powers to the Palestinians 
in the rest of the West Bank will begin after the blessed 'Id 
al-Adha. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-59781 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes096dd_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-096 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Arafat Remarks on Jihad, Jerusalem Draw Reaction </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Arafat Remarks on Jihad, Jerusalem Draw Reaction </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Further on Sha'th Explanation </H4>

<F P=102> JN1805111494 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Arabic 1005 GMT 18 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1805111494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political </F>
adviser to PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat by Sa'id Mu'addi in Cairo 
on 18 May from the "With the Midday Events" program -- recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Mu'addi] One last question, 
Dr. Nabil. Yasir 'Arafat's statements in Johannesburg drew 
angry reactions from the political leadership in Jerusalem, 
particularly the prime minister. What is your comment? 
  [Sha'th] My comment is that there is sometimes exaggeration, 
even in interpreting what President 'Arafat meant. Jihad in 
Islam is dual -- minor and major jihad. When Prophet Muhammad, 
may God's peace and blessing be upon him, conquered Mecca, he 
said: Minor jihad is now over and major jihad begins. The 
major jihad is the jihad of soul, work, construction, and all 
forms of struggle, not only the military jihad as, I believe, 
was understood in various places. Jihad for Jerusalem means 
struggle for the sake of insistence on presenting what we 
demand, that is, to have East Jerusalem as the capital of the 
Palestinian state. However, this will take place through 
various forms of peaceful struggle that will end with 
negotiations on the final status, an important part of which 
should be on Jerusalem. Our position on these negotiations is 
clear right now. This, I think, is what President 'Arafat meant. 
  [Mu'addi] One question, after the last, doctor. Was there a 
letter from Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin to Yasir 'Arafat on the 
status of Jerusalem? 
  [Sha'th] The letter Prime Minister Rabin exchanged with 
President 'Arafat, which was signed with the agreement as you 
may recall, stated that negotiations on the final status can 
begin as soon as possible but not after the beginning of the 
third year or the end of the second year after the start of the 
implementation of the Declaration of Principles. This means not 
later than 13 October 1995, namely, after one year and four or 
five months. These negotiations on the final status, as is 
clear in the Declaration of Principles, emphasize that Jerusalem 
is one of the five most important topics that will be discussed 
at these final negotiations. 
  [Mu'addi] Dr. Nabil Sha'th, member of the Palestinian 
National Authority, thank you very much. 
  [Sha'th] Thank you. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

