<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Rejects U.S. Report on Bosnia, Explosives </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Rejects U.S. Report on Bosnia, Explosives </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1605132794 Tehran IRNA in English 1311 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1605132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, May 16, IRNA -- Ministry of Defence and 
Armed Forces Logistics here Monday rejected a claim printed in 
U.S. daily THE WASHINGTON POST on sending explosives to Zagreb 
and described it as a new plot of U.S. media against the world 
Muslims. 
  THE WASHINGTON POST in its Friday issue quoted an unknown 
source, saying that using a jumbo jet to fly between Iran and 
Zagreb, Iran has transfered to Zagreb 60 tons of explosives and 
raw materials used in manufacturing arms. 
  Issuing a statement, the ministry said that the plots of the 
arrogant world media are merely aimed at tarnishing the humane 
image of the Islamic Republic of Iran. 
  Iran's Red Crescent Society (IRCS) has extended a large 
amount of relief aid to Bosnian Muslims since the start of the 
war between the Muslims and the Serbs. 
  The Islamic Republic of Iran recently opened its embassy in 
Sarajevo, the city which was under Serbian siege for a long 
time. Opening of Iranian Embassy in Sarajevo created a condition 
in which the Muslims and Croats reached understanding and 
created co-existence in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The Ministry of Defence and the Armed Forces Logistics said 
that raising such baseless claims especially at the time of 
opening of Iranian Embassy in Sarajevo and the announcement of 
Iran's repeated declaration of readiness to send 10,000 troops 
under the United Nations peace keeping force (UNPROFOR) to 
Bosnia are attempts to prevent Iran's diplomatic moves to end 
the massacre of the oppressed Muslims in Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

