<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Algeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Installation of National Council Expected 18 May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Installation of National Council Expected 18 May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1605224594 Algiers Radio Algiers Network in Arabic 2200 
GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1605224594 </F>
<F P=104>  Algiers Radio Algiers Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The installation of the Transitional National 
Council is expected to take place on 18 May. The news was 
carried by the Algerian news agency [APS], which quoted a 
well-informed source. The same source added that the 
Transitional National Council will be made up of 178 members, 22 
of whom will be leaders of political parties and 21 others 
leaders of associations. 
  Over to Aicha Degha for more details: 
  The Transitional National Council is a legislative body that 
will reinforce the constitutional apparatus stipulated in the 
document of consensus, which in turn constitutes a point of 
reference for the transitional period. This transitional period 
will last three years before a return to the electoral process. 
  According to the APS dispatch, the seats of some political 
parties that did not take in the national dialogue conference 
will remain vacant. The distribution of seats according to age 
shows that 52 members are 40 years old at the most and that the 
youngest member of the transitional national council was born in 
1969, while the oldest was born in 1918. 
  These figures indicate that the council takes into account 
all age groups. Moreover, many members of this body are highly 
educated university graduates. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

