<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-096 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iran-Pakistan Joint Economic Commission Meets </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Iran-Pakistan Joint Economic Commission Meets </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Memorandum of Understanding Signed </H4>

<F P=102> LD1805110194 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0930 GMT 18 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1805110194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] This morning, at the conclusion of the eighth 
session of the Iran-Pakistan joint economic commission, a 
memorandum of understanding was signed between the two 
countries. In this memorandum of understanding, signed by Road 
and Transport Minister Torkan and Wassim Ja'fari, the economic 
adviser to the prime minister of the Islamic Republic of 
Pakistan, agreement is reached on the joint construction of oil 
refinery [number not specified] and a gas pipeline to Pakistan, 
reconstruction of flood-damaged bridges in Pakistan, and 
construction of 1,300 km of roads in that country. 
  The memorandum also stressed the joint construction of the 
Kerman to Zahedan and Mirjaveh railway lines and improvement of 
the lines from Quetta to Taftan --by utilizing the two 
countries' financial and technical resources -- establishment of 
round-trip air routes between Zahedan and Quetta and between 
Lahore and Mashhad, and also the addition of a second railway 
service from Zahedan to Quetta. 
  The Iranian side, in this memorandum, has declared readiness 
to accept transit and trans-shipment of goods from Iranian ports 
and dredging of Pakistani ports and building of new ports at 
competitive international rates. 
  Other agreements reached in this memorandum include the 
provision of bank credits and customs facilities in order to 
speed up commercial services, transport of goods and passengers 
between Iran and Pakistan, and setting up of exclusive commodity 
exhibitions with the right to sell in each other's territory. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

