<H3> <TI>   Paper Backs Decision Not To Send Troops to Yemen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paper Backs Decision Not To Send Troops to Yemen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1605081894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0610 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1605081894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 16 May (MENA)--AL-AKHBAR praises the wisdom 
and courage of President Husni Mubarak, who loudly declared that 
Egypt will send no soldier to Yemen. Yemen, the paper says, is 
a country where brothers fight each other and launch air raids 
on northern and southern cities and villages. 
  In its editorial today, the paper says President Mubarak's 
decision to send no Egyptian or Arab forces to Yemen was made 
because any role these forces might play could endanger them or 
subject them to accusations from rival Yemeni parties. It adds: 
The harm would be great and could complicate the crisis in a 
tragedy that no one can resolve except those who created it. 
  The paper notes that a dialogue with words, not guns and 
tanks, is the only way to resolve the Yemeni crisis. It 
expresses the hope that the rival Yemeni parties will come to 
their senses, replace their weapons with more civilized means, a 
dialogue between brothers, resort to reason, and renounce 
differences to preserve Yemen's unity. 

</TEXT>

