<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres on Syrian Talks, Early-Warning Station </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peres on Syrian Talks, Early-Warning Station </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1905075794 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 0500 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1905075794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres in </F>
Oslo, by Mikhal Gazit and Ya'aqov Eylon in the studio -- live] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Eylon] Mr. Peres, with 
regard to the question of Syria, U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher's latest trip received a frosty reaction in 
Damascus. Do you share this impression? Is the issue stuck or 
do you see some progress? 
  [Peres] Look, we know how things work in Damascus. Until 
they give their agreement, frosty winds blow in all directions. 
People used to say that the difference between Syria and 
Lebanon is that with Lebanon it is very easy to reach an 
agreement but the agreement will be totally worthless, while 
with the Syrians it is very hard to reach an agreement but the 
agreement will stand. We will continue to act and strive until 
we convince the entire Middle East of the need for peace. In 
other words, we are the initiating party; we are not being 
dragged after anybody and we are not the offended party; we do 
not play sulking games. We have a very clear policy, and we 
must continue to act to implement it. 
  [Gazit] Mr. Peres, a banner headline in today's press says 
that Israel agrees to the establishment of a Syrian 
early-warning station in the Galilee. Do you have any idea what 
this is about? 
  [Peres] In my opinion, all these are premature speculations. 
I do not think we can discuss such details yet, because the 
problems between us and Syria are not of a technical nature but 
are a matter of principle. Only after we reach an agreement in 
principle will there be room to discuss technical issues. 
  [Gazit] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres, thank you very much. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

