<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-097 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Correspondent Views Situation in Gaza Strip </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Correspondent Views Situation in Gaza Strip </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1805191894 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 18 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1805191894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1700 GMT 18 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Arab affairs correspondent Ehud Ya'ari] </F>
  [Text] As Israel's disengagement from the Gaza Strip 
continues, here is some food for thought. The IDF [Israel 
Defense Forces] completed its pullout one week earlier than 
originally agreed upon in Cairo. This of course was carried out 
with the agreement of the PLO and the subsequent result is that 
only one third of the Palestinian forces slated to enter the 
area have indeed assumed their stations and the Palestinian 
Authority has yet to be established. 
  Second, the first impression made by the Fatah units 
entering 
the Gaza Strip was better than many Israelis had initially 
feared. Now, however, things are not looking so good. Looting 
has become quite widespread in the Gaza Strip and many telephone 
cables, air conditioners, and other objects have been stolen. 
The Fatah army has no money. It cannot afford to purchase gas 
for its vehicles or even food for the troops. In several 
places, complaints have been received that soldiers are eating 
at restaurants without paying. The majority of the troops have 
not received sufficient training in police work. 
  Third, if money does not arrive quickly from foreign 
sources, 
Israel may have to supply the Palestinians with urgent financial 
aid in order to pay for immediate expenditures. This sum could 
reach several million shekels. 
  Fourth, there is a great deal of tension among Fatah 
operatives in the Gaza Strip who fear that they are being pushed 
aside by 'Arafat's veteran officers. The open tension between 
the Fatah activists and the police commanders occasionally 
precludes cooperation. 
  On the political level, Hamas [Islamic Resistance Movement] 
has adopted a wait and see approach, while forbidding prisoners 
to sign any declarations of support for the peace process. 
  Meanwhile, Fatah has failed to drum up support for an 
agreement on the establishment of new municipal councils in 
Nabulus and Hebron. These are all labor pains, of course. 
'Arafat wants to differentiate between the Israeli withdrawal 
and the establishment of his authority. However, seeing as at 
the present time, there is no real authority in the Gaza Strip 
to replace Israel's partial control, difficulties can be 
expected even in the event of a best-case scenario. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-59891 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes097dd_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-097 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official on Fatah's Participation in Authority </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official on Fatah's Participation in Authority </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1805180694 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1335 GMT 18 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1805180694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, 18 May (MENA)--Al-Tayyib 'Abd-al-Rahim, 
Palestinian ambassador in Jordan and member of Fatah's Central 
Committee, stated that PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat will complete 
the formation of the Palestinian National Authority's council 
following the 'Id al-Adha holidays [21-24 May]. 
  In exclusive remarks to MENA correspondent in Tunis, 
'Abd-al-Rahim noted that the council will hold its first meeting 
in Cairo following the 'Id al-Adha to distribute the portfolios 
and responsibilities among its members. After that, all the 
council members will return to the homeland following the 
withdrawal of Israeli troops from Gaza and Jericho. 
'Abd-al-Rahim said that during its meeting in Tunis last night 
the Fatah Movement's Revolutionary Council decided to form 
several committees to work out a plan for the Fatah cadres to 
return to the homeland with specific assignments and 
instructions. Under this plan, each cadre could work in his 
area of specialization within the National Authority's 
institutions. 
  'Abd-al-Rahim added that the Fatah Movement's Revolutionary 
Council stressed the need for the movement to actively and 
effectively participate in the Palestinian National Authority to 
strengthen the Palestinian newborn authority. The Revolutionary 
Council, he added, backed the Central Committee's decision on 
the need for Fatah's effective participation in the National 
Authority's council and institutions in a way that reflects the 
movement's magnitude and role in the Palestinian struggle and to 
guarantee success for these institutions. 'Abd-al-Rahim added 
that this will ensure that the beginning in Gaza and Jericho 
will be the first step toward the liberation of the homeland and 
the restoration of the Palestinian people's national rights. He 
noted that the Revolutionary Council also made a decision 
securing the return of most of the movement's cadres to Gaza and 
Jericho so they could assume their responsibility and 
consolidate the newborn authority, which is the fruit of many 
long years of struggle by Fatah. 
  Concerning the reasons for the delay in signing the 
executive 
program of the Palestinian-Jordanian economic agreement, 
'Abd-al-Rahim said it was due to two points related to banking 
coordination and supervision in the self-rule area. He pointed 
out that in light of the Palestinian-Israeli agreement and the 
gains made by the Palestinians under the agreement, sound 
operational mechanisms had to be found to put the 
Palestinian-Jordanian agreement into effect and establish 
excellent ties between the two sides as well as between the 
Palestinians and other Arab countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-59892 </DOCNO>
