<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hekmatyar To Allow Supplies Into Kabul During 'Id </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hekmatyar To Allow Supplies Into Kabul During 'Id </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905093894 Tehran IRNA in English 0838 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905093894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Peshawar, May 19, IRNA -- The Afghan Coordination 
Council led by Prime Minister Golboddin Hekmatyar Wednesday [18 
May] announced that all roads leading to Kabul will be open for 
three days to allow transportation to Kabul during Eid-ul-Azha 
['Id al-Adha -- feast of immolation] Muslim festivity, May 12. 
  In a statement here, the council said that governmental as 
well as non-governmental organizations could carry all sorts of 
relief supplies to Kabul but with the guarantee that it would 
not be served for military purposes and would be distributed 
among the citizens of the city. 
  Kabul has been scene of the longest round of fightings since 
early January when allied forces of Hekmatyar and 'Abdol Rashid 
Dostum clashed with forces of President Borhanoddin Rabbani. 
  According to Afghan sources, the rival Afghan factions are 
presently locked in severe fighting in two provinces, Baghlan 
and Konduz, to capture strategic positions. Meanwhile, armed 
personnel of Hekmatyar and Sayyaf have been fighting since 
Tuesday in Maydan Shahr in Wardak Province. 

</TEXT>

