<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Strip Residents To Be Allowed To Enter Israel </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Strip Residents To Be Allowed To Enter Israel </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1805131794 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1200 GMT 18 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1805131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Residents of the Gaza Strip will be allowed to 
enter the boundaries of Israel after presenting a special 
certificate and undergoing a thorough security check. This 
statement was made by Police Minister Moshe Shahal to our 
correspondent Nisim Qeynan. Shahal added that responsibility for 
guarding the Green Line between the Gaza Strip and Israel will 
be handed over from the army to the Israel Police. In the next 
few days, the police command will take charge of the Lakhish 
region and the Southern Command's home front headquarters, thus 
creating a continuous and uniform command. The minister noted 
that within two weeks, he will announce the establishment of a 
sixth police district to be in charge of the autonomy. The 
police minister made the remarks during a tour of northern Gaza 
Strip today. 
  Commissioner Asaf Hefetz, Israel Police commander, expects 
no 
special problems in conducting safe passage between the Gaza 
Strip and Jericho. He expects tight cooperation between the 
Israeli and the autonomy police forces. Today, Commissioner 
Hefetz visited the Northern District for the first time since he 
assumed duty as police chief. He told our correspondent in the 
north Yo'av Aviv that he sees no change taking place on the 
ground following Yasir 'Arafat's call for a jihad. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

