<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jordanian Minister Departs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jordanian Minister Departs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1905104694 Baghdad INA in Arabic 0950 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN1905104694 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Baghdad, 19 May (INA)--Jordanian Education Minister 
Khalid al-'Umari and the delegation accompanying him left 
Baghdad today following a visit to Iraq which lasted several 
days. 
  In a statement to an Iraqi News Agency correspondent, 
al-'Umari said his visit to Iraq follows the implementation of 
an agreement signed between the two fraternal countries. The 
visit also aimed to study the efforts designed to enhance the 
educational system in Iraq following the unfair 30-state 
aggression and in view of the continued unjust blockade, he 
noted. 
  Al-'Umari said he was briefed on the Iraqi people's 
suffering 
as a result of the unfair blockade, on the embargo's negative 
repercussions on the educational process in Iraq, and on Iraqi 
achievements in various fields in order to reconstruct what was 
destroyed in the treacherous aggression of the 30-state 
alliance. He pointed out that the reconstruction campaign 
expresses both defiance and steadfastness, which emphasize that 
Iraq is now a model for all Arabs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

