<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rao Leads High-Level Delegation to U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rao Leads High-Level Delegation to U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Says Economic Reform `Irreversible' </H4>

<F P=102> BK1605110594 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0245 
GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1605110594 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The prime minister has asked the nonresident 
Indians, NRIs, to play their legitimate role in the speedy 
development of the country. Addressing a large gathering of 
NRIs in New York, Mr. Narasimha Rao asked them to evaluate for 
themselves the reform process without attaching any emotions. 
He emphatically stated that the economic changes underway in 
India are irreversible. The prime minister invited them to take 
advantage of the opportunities and invest in the country to help 
expand and strengthen the economic liberalization process. He 
said that structural hurdles posed at the initial stages have 
been overcome and there is a turnaround now. The prime minister 
appreciated the good work being carried out by the NRIs in 
various walks of life outside the country. 
  Our correspondent Rama Rao, covering the prime minister's 
visit, reports from New York that Mr. Narasimha Rao will be 
meeting the captains of industry at Houston today in the second 
leg of his visit to the United States. He described the visit 
as a step towards a strong, friendly, and cordial cooperation 
between the two great democracies of the world. During his 
one-day stay in Houston, the prime minister will be meeting the 
chief executive officers and presidents of the major companies 
under the auspices of the Greater Houston Partnership. The 
partnership brings together over 2,000 companies based in the 
city. The mayor of Houston will be presenting the keys of the 
city to Mr. Narasimha Rao. The prime minister will attend an 
Indian community reception before leaving for Boston tomorrow. 
  Our special correspondent Bhupal Inder Saini reports from 
Washington: 
  [Begin Saini recording] One of the primary objectives of the 
prime minister's goodwill visit to the United States is to 
explore the potentials and opportunities of stepping up 
Indo-American cooperation in the economic sphere. The United 
States is already India's largest trading partner and the 
economic reforms undertaken by New Delhi under Mr. Narasimha 
Rao's leadership had created tremendous opportunities for 
further stepping up economic links and trade. Significantly, a 
large number of leading Indian businessmen are also in the 
United States to tap the potential for tie-ups with American 
companies. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-59957 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes097_r_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-097 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rao Leads High-Level Delegation to U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rao Leads High-Level Delegation to U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Stresses Indian-U.S. Investment </H4>

<F P=102> BK1605153294 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1605153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Top U.S. business executives have offered to make 
big investments in India. The rich Indian-American community 
has also indicated plans to provide their expertise and money 
for giving a push to the market friendly reform process. At 
their separate meetings with the prime minister, now on an 
official tour of the United States, both American companies and 
the NRIs [nonresident Indians] appreciated the economic 
liberalization policy and said it has transformed India into a 
prospective market for greater inflow of funds. Mr. Narasimha 
Rao assured them that the Foreign Investment Promotion Board 
will look into any irritants in materializing their projects. 
  Our correspondent Rama Rao covering the prime minister's 
visit reports that the NRI plans include investments in highway 
construction and communications, as also mobilization of at 
least $2 billion every year. Mr. Narasimha Rao told the NRIs 
that they can play their legitimate role in the 
industrialization of the country and their investments have to 
increase as they go along. 
  Addressing a large section of the Indian-American community 
in New York, the prime minister said India means business and 
the future course is clear. His current visit is to project the 
giant leap the country is poised to take in industrial 
development and to give a personal undertaking over the 
irreversibility of the changed course. Mr. Rao asked the NRIs 
to participate in the present efforts based on their sound 
economic judgment. Commending the NRIs for the good work done 
in the country where they are living, he said they should keep 
it up. About Indo-U.S. ties, the prime minister said these need 
to be strong and friendly, not only for mutual benefit but for 
the future of mankind as a whole. The importance of his visit, 
he said, goes beyond the scope of normal bilateral relations. 
  The prime minister has since arrived in Houston on the 
second 
leg of his American tour. Mr. Narasimha Rao is scheduled to 
meet the chief executives and presidents of major companies 
under the auspices of the Greater Houston Partnership. The 
partnership brings together over 2,000 companies based in the 
city. Later, the mayor of Houston will be presenting the keys 
of the city to Mr. Narasimha Rao. He will also attend a 
reception by the Indian community before leaving for Boston 
tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

