<DOCNO> FBIS4-59958 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes097_r_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-097 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rao Leads High-Level Delegation to U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rao Leads High-Level Delegation to U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Courts `Top American Companies' </H4>

<F P=102> BK1705053394 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0245 
GMT 17 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1705053394 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Top American companies have evinced interest in 
investing in the Indian infrastructural sector. At the 
roundtable meeting with the prime minister, Mr. P.V. Narasimha 
Rao, in Houston the chief executives of several companies 
expressed an upbeat mood to invest in India. Over 100 chief 
executive officers of major companies attended the meeting. The 
prime minister outlined the salient features of the economic 
reforms and invited American businessmen to become partners for 
further mutual benefit. 
  Our correspondent Rama Rao accompanying the prime minister 
reports that for the first time since the launching of economic 
reforms, the foreign investors focussed attention on specific 
pattern of their projects. In another significant change, the 
investors themselves have analyzed the relative advantages of 
various markets in South Asia and have ranked India well above 
others. Our correspondent further states that the new projects 
outlined at the meeting include the setting up of a commercial 
bank, mining and exploitation of bauxite in Andhra Pradesh and 
Orissa, and a computer company. 
  A heavy schedule awaits the prime minister when he arrives 
in 
Washington DC tonight on the last leg of his week-long visit to 
the United States. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

