<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Christopher's Damascus Visit Reported, Assessed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Christopher's Damascus Visit Reported, Assessed </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Issues `Remarkably Difficult' </H4>

<F P=102> JN1905055294 Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network in 
Arabic 0415 GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1905055294 </F>
<F P=104>  Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] U.S. Secretary of State Christopher and his 
accompanying delegation left Damascus at 1615 yesterday. He was 
seen off at Damascus International Airport by Foreign Minister 
Faruq al-Shar', the Syrian ambassador in Washington, and the 
U.S. ambassador in Damascus. 
  The U.S. secretary of state arrived in Cairo yesterday, 
Wednesday, evening. He met with Egyptian President Husni 
Mubarak. Christopher said he believes that Syria is serious 
about Middle East peace. 
  Following his meeting with President Mubarak, Christopher 
told reporters that the negotiations are facing a long road, and 
that the issues are remarkably difficult. 
  In press statements on his arrival in Cairo, Christopher 
said 
he held good and constructive talks with officials in Syria and 
Israel. He explained that during his meetings several proposals 
were discussed. These proposals concern achieving a 
breakthrough in the peace process on the Syrian track. 
Christopher expressed optimism despite the existence of some 
difficult topics that need further talks with both sides. He 
said he naturally found points of convergence and difference. 
However, we will continue the rounds of talks to reach a 
solution and achieve a breakthrough on all tracks, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

