<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Correspondent Denies Story on Government Reshuffle </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Correspondent Denies Story on Government Reshuffle </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1905113094 Amman AL-DUSTUR in Arabic 19 May 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> JN1905113094 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-DUSTUR </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From "Letters to the Editor"] </F>
  [Text] Mr. Chief Editor: 
  Greetings, 
  With reference to the report published yesterday on the 
formation of a new Government in Syria under "Major General" 
Hikmat al-Shihabi, I would like to clarify the following: 
  First: The report was datelined ""Damascus, AL-DUSTUR" which 
suggests that I was its source. This is untrue. I had nothing 
to do with that report. 
  Second: It seems that the report did not originate from 
Damascus in the first place. The chief of staff in Syria holds 
the rank of a "lieutenant general" and not a "major general," as 
mentioned in the report. This makes one conclude that the 
author of the report is very far from understanding Syrian 
affairs. 
  Third: Lieutenant General Hikmat al-Shihabi is widely 
respected among all Syrian and non-Syrian circles. I find it 
inappropriate to mention his name just like that whenever one 
wants to talk about the a government formation. 
  Fourth: There is nothing in Syrian political circles to 
suggest any potential reshuffle in the current Syrian 
Government, which is headed by Engineer Mahmud al-Zu'bi, 
especially since it recorded several achievements which cannot 
be mentioned here. 
  Sixth [as published]: The concerned circles in Damascus have 
not commented on this report. Nor have they reacted to similar 
reports published in the past. 
  I will be grateful if you publish this clarification. With 
my best regards. 
  [Signed] 'Ali Jamalu, AL-DUSTUR correspondent in Damascus 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

