<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Council of Ministers Discusses Country's Conditions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Council of Ministers Discusses Country's Conditions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1805141794 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1200 GMT 18 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1805141794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Council of Ministers held its regular meeting 
this morning under the acting prime minister, Dr. Muhammad Sa'id 
al-'Attar. The Council discussed issues on the agenda, 
particularly reports presented to it on the military and 
security situation and the economic, supply, and information 
conditions under the current comprehensive national 
confrontation of the plot of apostasy, rebellion, and secession, 
which led the country to this situation with the aim of 
realizing the secessionists' desire which is opposed to the 
people and their unity and democracy, and undermining the 
constitutional legitimacy. 
  After discussing the various reports, the Council expressed 
its satisfaction with the great success of the brave Yemeni 
Armed Forces who are defending unity and legitimacy in 
confronting the forces of insurgency and secession. The Council 
emphasized the tasks and duties which the various ministries and 
departments of public utilities are expected to perform during 
the present circumstances. Foremost of these tasks are tackling 
and repairing the disorders which the insurgent secessionists 
planned, and dealing with the living conditions and the economic 
and supply situations in the country. This requires the 
implementation of a speedy plan to make available all the 
necessary needs of consumer goods in all the republic's 
governorates. 
  The Council decided to continue its meetings. The next 
session, which will be held tomorrow, will be devoted to 
discussing the detailed work of the executive and administrative 
sector and of each ministry. The Council agreed to the Civil 
Service Ministry's proposals concerning the holidays for the two 
great occasions, the blessed 'Id al-Adha and the fourth 
anniversary of the Yemeni Republic. The Council assigned each 
minister the task of fixing these holidays in a manner that will 
not affect the daily work in all ministries and public utilities 
during the present circumstances. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

