<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Qatar </F>
<H3> <TI>   Basindwah Ends Visit to Qatar, Returns Home </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Basindwah Ends Visit to Qatar, Returns Home </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1805181794 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1700 GMT 18 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1805181794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] His Highness Shaykh Khalifah Bin-Hamad Al Thani, 
amir of the State of Qatar, today received Yemeni Foreign 
Minister brother Muhammad Salim Basindwah, who conveyed a 
message to his highness from brother Lieutenant General 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih, chairman of the Presidential Council and 
supreme commander of the Armed Forces, dealing with the 
situation in our country, issues of mutual interest, and the 
close relations between the two fraternal countries. 
  The Qatari News Agency said that Shaykh Khalifah Bin-Hamad 
Al 
Thani had regretted the human and material losses in Yemen, 
pointed out that what is taking place in Yemen is an internal 
affair, and stressed that the events will end in a manner that 
will preserve Yemen's unity and historic achievements and will 
restore Yemen's security and stability. The meeting was 
attended by Shaykh Hamad Bin-Khalifah, heir apparent and defense 
minister, Shaykh Hamad Bin- Jasim, minister of foreign affairs, 
and brother 'Abd-al-Wahhab al-Jahhaf, our country's ambassador 
to the fraternal State of Qatar. 
  Foreign Minister brother Muhammad Salim Basindwah returned 
to 
Sanaa after working visits to Egypt, Jordan, Syria, Bahrain, the 
United Arab Emirates, Oman, and Qatar that lasted several days. 
  In a statement to SABA', the foreign minister said that 
during his tour, he conveyed letters from Lt. Gen. 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih, chairman of the Presidential Council and 
supreme commander of the Armed Forces, to his brothers the 
leaders and kings of Egypt, Jordan, Syria, Bahrain, the United 
Arab Emirates, Oman, and Qatar, explaining that the letters 
concerned the latest developments in the situation in Yemen, as 
well as bilateral issues of common interest. 

</TEXT>

