<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> United Arab Emirates </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shaykh Zayid, al-Bid Exchange Views on Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shaykh Zayid, al-Bid Exchange Views on Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1905103894 Abu Dhabi United Arab Emirates Radio Network in 
Arabic 0930 GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1905103894 </F>
<F P=104>  Abu Dhabi United Arab Emirates Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] His Highness Shaykh Zayid Bin-Sultan Al Nuhayyan, 
United Arab Emirates [UAE] President, last night received a 
phone call from 'Ali Salim al-Bid, vice chairman of the Yemeni 
Presidential Council, within the framework of the ongoing 
contacts and the intensive efforts his highness exerts with 
respect to the Yemeni crisis. 
  Discussion during the telephone contact dealt with the 
situation in the Yemeni arena. Shaykh Zayid reiterated the 
UAE's pressing desire for a cease-fire, pointing out that it is 
regrettable that Yemeni President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih still 
insists on pursuing the fighting in spite of the recurrent 
sincere calls his highness has addressed to his excellency since 
the very first moment of the war of brothers. His highness 
Shaykh Zayid Bin-Sultan Al Nuhayyan further said during the 
telephone contact: I have repeatedly appealed to the Yemeni 
president. I have exerted all possible effort to immediately 
stop firing. We have said we are ready to pursue mediation 
efforts in Yemen with every means we have to sincerely and 
loyally reconcile the brothers so Yemen remains stable and so 
differences among them will be submitted to the fraternal Yemeni 
people whom will decide on them and have their final say, 
instead of this recourse to arms. The Yemeni people are a free 
people like all others, and their fate does not belong to anyone. 
  He added: The Yemeni people know where their real interest 
lies and their happiness and stability are the objectives that 
all should seek. 
  From his part, the Yemeni vice president called on the head 
of state in the telephone contact to pursue with his well-known 
wisdom his persistent efforts with his brother Arab leaders to 
stop the raging battles and the bloody war and to resort to 
fraternal dialogue to reach a political solution to the crisis 
out of concern for the safety of Yemeni citizens and to 
safeguard national unity. 
  The Yemeni vice chairman added: Why this shedding of blood 
and the fighting among the sons of the one people for one or two 
persons? Has the aggression against the south come from an 
enemy of the Yemeni people? It is inconceivable that a dialogue 
be held between the two parties while the fighting continues. 
No side can be attacked and remain idle and accept the 
imposition of a solution on it. The language of force and the 
military method in settling differences is rejected and portends 
dire consequences. The homeland's interest should be given 
priority over any other interest. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

