<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Linguistic Argument' Cited Over Jihad Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Linguistic Argument' Cited Over Jihad Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2005103294 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 20 May 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> PM2005103294 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Fatinah al-Dajani: "Safiyah: Emerging </F>
Palestinian Entity Modest, but Promising Start"] 
  [Excerpt] London -- 'Afif Safiyah, Palestinian delegate to 
the UK, has said that there is a pragmatic wing inside the 
Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) which should be encouraged. 
He pointed out that the movement has so far acted "very 
responsibly." He said that the Palestinian entity emerging in 
Gaza and Jericho is a modest, but promising start. 
  Replying to the clamor over the content of a tape of 
Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat during his meeting with 
Muslims in a South African mosque, in which he called for jihad 
for the sake of Jerusalem, he said that there is always 
linguistic argument about the concept and meaning of the word 
jihad. He pointed out that 'Arafat called for jihad for the 
sake of Jerusalem, "that is, to strive collectively to liberate 
Jerusalem peacefully." Safiyah said that Israeli Prime Minister 
Yitzhaq Rabin continues to speak of Jerusalem as the eternal 
capital of Israel. "What is important is the international will 
represented in the resolutions adopted by the Security Council 
and the General Assembly, which consider Jerusalem an occupied 
territory from which Israel must withdraw." 
  In a lecture delivered in London the evening of the day 
before yesterday at the invitation of the "Council for 
Arab-British Understanding" (CABU), Safiyah dealt with a number 
of controversial issues on the Palestinian scene, including the 
peace process since the Madrid and Washington negotiations 
through to the Oslo and Cairo negotiations, in addition to the 
future of the PLO, the Palestinian economy, and Hamas. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

