<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Musa on Christopher Talks, 'Arafat Jihad Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Musa on Christopher Talks, 'Arafat Jihad Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1905152894 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 1400 GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1905152894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa has stated that the 
situation in Yemen is regrettable. He added that no good will 
come of the military action, either in the near or distant 
future. He noted that the situation of Yemen is still on the 
agenda of the Arab League, adding that the Arab League Council's 
emergency session is still in session. Everybody, he said, is 
following the developments and events there. 
  Regarding the Syrian-Israeli peace track, the foreign 
minister said that diplomatic action will continue in the coming 
days to narrow the differences between Syria and Israel. He 
pointed out that U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher's 
talks in Cairo showed that differences do exist between the two 
sides. The talks also showed the feasibility of continuing 
efforts to bridge the gap as much as possible, he added. 
  Answering a question on Egypt's stand on the situation in 
Somalia, Musa said that Egypt is ready to intervene once again 
to reconcile the parties in Somalia in view of Egypt's status, 
role, and connections in consolidating unity in Somalia. 
  [Cairo MENA in Arabic at 1445 GMT on 19 May carries a 
further 
report on Musa's statement, which adds: 
  ["Asked about the disagreement between the Palestinians and 
Israelis over Palestinian president Yasir 'Arafat's remarks in 
Johannesburg in which he called for a jihad for the sake of 
Jerusalem, Musa said: There are many statements from both 
sides. The important thing, he added, is for these statements 
to serve what has been achieved and prepare the ground for the 
coming stages of negotiations between the two sides. He 
stressed that the Palestinian efforts, which we are all behind, 
must be directed toward giving momentum to a fruitful 
negotiation process to restore full Palestinian rights as part 
of the land for peace principle."] 

</TEXT>

