<F P=106> [Report by Shirin Dahruj from Port Said] </F>
  [Text] Dr. Usamah al-Baz, first Foreign Ministry under 
secretary and director of the President's Office for Political 
Affairs, has denied that the Gulf states are helping the 
extremist groups in Egypt. He stressed that the Gulf countries 
know that any harm to Egypt's security will bring harm to them. 
  Speaking at a seminar at the Education College in Port Said, 
al-Baz noted that any outside military intervention in Yemen 
will further complicate the crisis. He stressed that Egypt will 
not intervene militarily in Yemen but will hold intensive 
political and diplomatic contacts to end the conflict. Al-Baz 
cautioned against conflicts among Arab states. He noted that 
such conflicts would give a bad impression of the Arab nation 
worldwide. 
  Al-Baz pointed out that the notion of a Middle East market 
was first raised by Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres. He 
pointed out that before establishing a Middle East market, an 
Arab world must be established first. 

</TEXT>

