<DOCNO> FBIS4-60072 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes098_l_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-098 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gur Notes `Doubts' About PLO Accord Execution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gur Notes `Doubts' About PLO Accord Execution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1805123994 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1000 GMT 18 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1805123994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Deputy Defense Minister Mordekhay Gur says that 
there are doubts about the implementation of autonomy. There 
have been shooting incidents with casualties, and there is a 
feeling that the situation is unclear and that working patterns 
have as yet to be established. The deputy defense minister made 
these observations during a visit to the Qatif Bloc on the first 
day of the IDF's [Israel Defense Forces] redeployment. 
  Our Army affairs correspondent Karmela Menashe reports that 
referring to 'Arafat's remarks in South Africa, Deputy Minister 
Gur said the PLO chief's conduct was beyond any political or 
human ethics, and was inexcusable. He did not believe, however, 
that the agreement was in any danger. 
  Tzvi Handel, head of the Hof 'Aza Regional Council, told the 
deputy minister that a car stolen yesterday from the Eley Sinai 
settlement was today found in the possession of a Palestinian 
policeman. 

</TEXT>

